Germany: A Budget Fetish That Costs a Lot
FRANKFURT – The European Central Bank (ECB) is facing fierce attacks in Germany, a country that has long prided itself on defending the principle of central bank independence.
It was Germany that insisted on this principle being included in the criteria set out in the Maastricht Treaty, which establishes the conditions for membership of the European Monetary Union.
For many members of the Economic and Monetary Union (EMU), granting independence to their central bank in order to join the eurozone implied a change in political regime.
Thus, the independence of the Bank of France, during the referendum on ratification of the Maastricht Treaty in 1992, was one of the strongest arguments in the campaign against joining the euro.
In today's Germany, on the contrary, it has become commonplace, so to speak, to put pressure on the central bank.
For several months now, even the finance minister, Wolfgang Schäuble, regularly comments on the monetary policy of the European Central Bank (ECB).
Schaüble's interventions target the very core of what constitutes the central bank's independence.
While he does not seek to redefine the objective of monetary policy (this "price stability," in the old language of the Bundesbank), he nevertheless offers his advice on the tools the ECB should use and how it should use them to achieve such an aim.
There are precedents for this.
In 1998, Oskar Lafontaine, then Germany's finance minister, gave his good advice to the first president of the ECB, Wim Duisenberg, on how to conduct monetary policy (Lafontaine's goal was ultimately to create a target zone for exchange rates).
Duisenberg, with his typically Dutch brevity, replied that there was nothing incongruous about a politician expressing his opinion on monetary policy (in Germany, this was absolutely unusual). "Yet," he added, "it would be entirely abnormal to take [his] suggestions into account."

Respect for the independence of monetary policy has long been a central element of the German Stabilitätkultur ("stability culture").
The founding act of the Bundesbank's reputation for strict independence was its refusal to yield to the exhortations of Chancellor Konrad Adenauer, who wanted it to contain the rise in interest rates, in 1956.
At that time, France did not see things the same way.
Charles de Gaulle was on the verge of creating the Fifth Republic, with a Bank of France accountable to the finance minister.
But that was another time.
Following the various crises that have shaken the EMU, monetary policy has increasingly tended to replace fiscal policy.
Would the old dogma have become obsolete?
Europe remains highly vulnerable; the median inhabitant of the EMU has already lost ten years, and what is even more worrying, we are close to a critical situation.
The United States, nevertheless, are doing better.
Despite a political deadlock difficult to manage, they have succeeded in addressing the macroeconomic problem (the weakness of aggregate demand) they were facing by launching expansionary fiscal and monetary policies.
The United States have also better managed their banking problems, which, initially, were much more severe than in Europe.
(There is obviously a strong interaction between the measures that can be taken in both areas.
The more robust an economy is, the more profitable its banks are and the more capable they are of fulfilling their function: financing the economy.
However, the independence of the ECB is less threatened by the good advice of a finance minister than by the lack of support from the population.
Indeed, the famous autonomy of the Bundesbank was based less on its legal status than on the unwavering support (justified by its performance) of German citizens.
It is exactly the opposite with the ECB.
Voces are being heard, notably in Germany, to subject it to greater pressure.
But the greatest threat to the autonomy of the ECB lies in the unbearable burden that weighs on its shoulders.
The less fiscal policy is called upon to stabilize production, the more central banks are de facto forced to take on this objective (unless, of course, they are designed to let nature take its course and allow the economy to fall into stagnation, or even worse).
The political result of this chain of events is a very clear regression toward nationalism, from the right and the left, in all the countries of the EMU, including Germany.
The rise of nationalism is almost a logical corollary of the policies pursued.
It is endogenous.
And there too, Germany leads the way, with its obsession with schwarze Null, with budget balance, against all winds and tides.
In Germany, deficits are frowned upon, not only from an arithmetic perspective, but also from a moral standpoint, even if this defies economic common sense and resembles clientelism.
At the end of the 19th century, the main German specialists in public finance, including Albert Schäffle and Adolph Wagner, formulated a "golden rule" according to which current expenditures must be financed, on average, by current revenues.
Public expenditures, and the resources they require, are justified by their usefulness.
This amounts to saying that investments aimed at improving productivity – equipment expenditures – can be financed with debt, the servicing of which is ensured by the growth of incomes and the tax base associated with them.
This classical approach has been institutionalized in a useful concept: the distinction between current expenditures and investment expenditures, which is still practiced at the municipal level in Germany (and Austria).
This is crucial, because in Germany, about 50% of public investment expenditures are managed at this level (a proportion that has decreased, as the municipal share was two-thirds at the beginning of the 1990s).
These expenditures are consistent with the support of the competitiveness of German small and medium-sized enterprises (mittlestand).
But compared to the beginning of the 1990s and at constant prices, investment expenditures have decreased by about 15%.
For more than a decade now, they have been insufficient to maintain the capital stock.
If this is not how one prepares for the future, this is how one undermines productivity and prosperity.
In short, schwarze Null goes against the intended goal.
Outdated infrastructure (certainly not as much as in the United States) has become a real problem for Germany.
Furthermore, the budgetary frugality of German leaders goes beyond German borders and its effects are amplified by the monetary union, which does not have exchange rates to adapt to national particularities.
Of course, the European monetary union is imperfect.
But turning the only institution willing to "do what needs to be done" to bring the EMU back on track into a scapegoat is a very bad idea.
That the states use, where it exists, the budgetary space they have at their disposal to relieve pressure on the ECB would be a much better strategy.
Germany, without doubt, enjoys a certain margin of maneuver in this regard.
